CSS Compilation: A Breakdown
CSS compilation is the process of transforming preprocessed CSS code (written in languages like Sass or LESS) into standard CSS that can be understood by web browsers. This compilation step is essential because browsers only recognize standard CSS syntax.

How CSS Compilation Works with Preprocessors
Writing Preprocessed Code: Developers write CSS code using a preprocessor language like Sass or LESS. This code often includes features like variables, nested rules, mixins, and functions, which are not supported by standard CSS.
Compilation: A compiler or processing tool is used to convert the preprocessed code into standard CSS. This tool parses the preprocessed code, interprets its features, and generates the equivalent standard CSS.
Usage in Web Projects: The compiled CSS is then included in web projects, typically using a <link> tag in the HTML <head> section. Browsers can directly interpret and apply the compiled CSS to the webpage.
Steps Involved in Compiling Sass to CSS
Parsing: The Sass compiler analyzes the Sass code, breaking it down into its individual components (rules, selectors, declarations, etc.).
Variable Evaluation: Variables defined in the Sass code are replaced with their corresponding values.
Mixin Expansion: Mixins (reusable code blocks) are expanded and their contents are inserted into the appropriate places.
Nested Rule Flattening: Nested rules are flattened into their equivalent standard CSS structure.
Function Evaluation: Functions defined in the Sass code are executed, and their results are used in the generated CSS.
Output Generation: The compiler generates the final CSS code, which is a standard CSS file that can be used in web projects.
Example: Sass to CSS Compilation
Original Sass Code:

Code snippet
$primary-color: #007bff;

.button {
  background-color: $primary-color;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  cursor: pointer;
}
Use code with caution.

Compiled CSS:

CSS
.button {
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  cursor: pointer;
}
Use code with caution.

In this example, the Sass compiler replaces the $primary-color variable with its value (#007bff) and flattens the nested rule structure to produce the equivalent standard CSS.

Note: The specific compilation process and output may vary slightly depending on the Sass compiler or processing tool used.